$(document).ready(function () {
    $('.article-top-widget').on('click', '.ati-toggle-trigger', function () {
        $(this).find('.icon-general-add, .icon-minus').toggleClass('icon-minus icon-general-add');
        $(this).siblings('.ati-toggle-content').toggleClass('hide');
    });

    // In Chrome, an anchor tag with target="_blank" and a "mailto:" href opens a new tab/window as well as the email client
    // I suspect this behavior will be corrected in the future
    // Remove the target="_blank"
    $('ul.wi-affiliationList').find('a[href^="mailto:"]').each(function () {
        $(this).removeAttr('target');
    });
});

div.p:
Ted Underwood’s (2014) classification of text at the page level found that the following features were most predictive of poetry:
number of different word types on page/number of words on page;
number of capitalized lines on page/number of all lines;
words on page/mean words per page in the volume being processed;
total words on page; and
proportion of lines ending with punctuation.

and, that these features argued most strongly against poetry:
exclamation points normalized for word count;
total words on page/total lines on page;
square of (number of different word types on page/number of words on page); and
(number of different word types on page/number of words on page) multiplied by the log of ‘sumAllWords’.
